<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06065169 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06065169 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Ron Burda -- Mercury News; MAKING GOOD -- Rick Rubino neverbargained for rain in a drought.  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  SCHOOL; OFFICIAL; BEHAVIOR; UNUSUAL; STUDENT; READING; CONTEST; CAUSE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Principal Rick Rubino is a man of principle.;    Four weeks ago, while we werein the throes  of the fifth year of drought, the Glenmoor Elementary principalpromised students that, rain or shine, he  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  PROMISE LEFT HIM HIGH AND WETEDUCATOR WHO CHALLENGED KIDS TO READ PAYSTHE PRICE ON ROOF  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Inside Our Towns  </MEMO><TEXT>  would spend the school day on the roof if they read 90,000 minutes at homeover three weeks. That's 1,500 hours, or 2.6 hours for each of the school's570 students. It was the idea of reading specialists Claire MacFadyen andKathi Sherrod, and their plan called for students to push away the televisionset and read between 10 and 15 minutes a night. The students turned in 102,189minutes.;    &quot;There was a drought,&quot; Rubino said as rain pelted his umbrellaMonday and he tried to explain why he agreed to do this. &quot;I thought it wouldbe very comfortable.&quot;;    Not so, he found out as a rainstorm swept across thearea, interrupting the drought for a few days. It rained so much Monday hecouldn't get his desk and telephone up on the roof to do some work.;    But hedid manage to get a large wooden box up and write a newsletter to parentsexplaining the positive things he learned from the ordeal.;    Parents andteachers brought hot beverages and muffins to Rubino, who wore a green rainsuit (&quot;school color,&quot; he explained) over his regular principal attire.Students at recess, with upturned faces, chanted, &quot;Rain, rain, rain,&quot; andasked him whether he worried about acid rain or thunderbolts. &quot;No-o-o-o,&quot; hesaid as he scanned the horizon.;    Besides encouraging a video generation toread books, Rubino should be placed in the hero category for action above andbeyond the call of duty, so to speak.;    When he said he was going to stayput on the roof all day, he meant it.;    &quot;No potty break,&quot; he promised.;   &quot;I did it,&quot; he said as he came down the ladder at 3 p.m. &quot;But just barely.&quot;; NAMES, NAMES, NAMES: The 570 students who put their principal out in the rainMonday read for 21,769 minutes the first week, then picked up and turned in35,924 the second week and 44,496 the last week. Finishing in the top 10 wereAbraham Park, a third-grader with 2,370 minutes; Ida Friar, fourth grade,1,627; Malarie Mattern, fourth grade, 1,423; Michel Khristo, fourth grade,1,303; Michele Holcomb, sixth grade, 1,266; Emily Kidder, fifth grade, 1,175;Holly Warren, first grade, 932; Lisa Mullins, third grade, 907; JenniferMiller, fourth grade, 896; and Joshua Nicolaysen, fifth grade, and MelissaFields, who both turned in 845 minutes.;     THE CHAMP: The MercNews' ownCheryl Champ, retail sales representative in the Fremont office, was recentlynamed Woman of the Year by Pathfinder chapter of the American Business Women'sAssociation.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Dennis Rockstroh  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Alameda County/AM  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910305  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  March  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  478  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday March 5, 199100065169,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>